First, find the height of I<sub>B</sub>I<sub>C</sub>D (which is perpendicular to BC).  Since I<sub>B</sub>I<sub>C</sub> is perpendicular to E<sub>B</sub>E<sub>C</sub> (due to the parallelogram formed), and D is the intersection of the vertical line from I<sub>B</sub>I<sub>C</sub> and BC, this height is the same as the inradius * **r** of triangle ABC.

The area of a triangle is ½*base*height. Therefore, the area of triangle I<sub>B</sub>I<sub>C</sub>D is (½)* I<sub>B</sub>I<sub>C</sub> * r = (½) * 1 * *r* = **r/2**.



* **Area of quadrilateral I<sub>B</sub>I<sub>C</sub>E<sub>B</sub>E<sub>C</sub>:** This area is given as 7:

Area(I<sub>B</sub>I<sub>C</sub>E<sub>B</sub>E<sub>C</sub>) = 7

